</div>
</div>
<p>A <b>network switch</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Computer_networking_device" title="Computer networking device">computer networking device</a> that connects <a href="/wiki/Computer_network" title="Computer network">network</a> <a href="/wiki/Network_segment" title="Network segment">segments</a>.</p>
<p>The term commonly refers to a <a href="/wiki/Network_bridge" title="Network bridge">Network bridge</a> that processes and routes data at the <a href="/wiki/Data_link_layer" title="Data link layer" class="mw-redirect">Data link layer</a> (layer 2) of the <a href="/wiki/OSI_model" title="OSI model">OSI model</a>. Switches that additionally process data at the <a href="/wiki/Network_layer" title="Network layer" class="mw-redirect">Network layer</a> (layer 3 and above) are often referred to as Layer 3 switches or <a href="/wiki/Multilayer_switch" title="Multilayer switch">Multilayer switches</a>.</p>
<p>The term <b>network switch</b> does not generally encompass unintelligent or passive network devices such as <a href="/wiki/Network_hub" title="Network hub" class="mw-redirect">hubs</a> and <a href="/wiki/Repeaters" title="Repeaters" class="mw-redirect">repeaters</a>.</p>
<p>The first <a href="/wiki/Ethernet" title="Ethernet">Ethernet</a> switch was introduced by <a href="/wiki/Kalpana_(company)" title="Kalpana (company)">Kalpana</a> in 1990. <sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
